<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,638,346,1126]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,280,346,367]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gyllenhal" authorityYear="1808" box="[373,458,346,367]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Histerini">Histerini</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="MARSEUL" authorityYear="1853" box="[470,601,346,367]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[470,601,346,367]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Margarinotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are generally recognizable by the presence of a complete outer subhumeral elytral stria. Most species have multidenticulate, rounded protibiae, with only poorly developed marginal teeth, with the protibia shallowly excavate between the teeth on the anterior surface. However, they are most unambiguously diagnosed by their distinctive aedeagus, with an elongate median lobe with articulated dorsal armature that rotates upwards when extruded (
<figureCitation box="[543,610,581,602]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[175,207,596,615]" captionTargetBox="[166,636,203,554]" captionTargetId="figure-550@3.[151,638,183,572]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Margarinotus ephemeralis and Margarinotus remotus, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. ephemeralis, dorsal view.B.M. ephemeralis, lateral view.C. M. ephemeralis, apical view of gonopore. D. M. remotus, apical view of gonopore. E. M. remotus, dorsal view. F. M. remotus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892934/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[620,634,581,602]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[731,763,888,907]" captionTargetBox="[712,1186,187,856]" captionTargetId="figure-560@4.[707,1194,183,864]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 4. Margarinotus spp., median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. fractifrons, dorsal view. B. M. fractifrons, lateral view. C. M. harrisii, dorsal view. D. M. harrisii, lateral view. E. M. rectus, dorsal view. F. M. rectus, lateral view. G. M. pluto, dorsal view. H. M. pluto, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892940/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,164,608,629]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[197,229,1567,1586]" captionTargetBox="[175,657,1158,1542]" captionTargetId="figure-480@6.[173,660,1091,1544]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 5. Margarinotus umbilicatus and Margarinotus umbrosus, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. umbilicatus, dorsal view. B. M. umbilicatus, lateral view. C. M. umbilicatus, apical view of gonopore (variant). D. M. umbilicatus (typical form), apical view of gonopore. E. M. umbrosus, apical view of gonopore. F. M. umbrosus, dorsal view. G. M. umbrosus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892946" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892946/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[176,189,608,629]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[197,230,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[174,648,1049,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-672@8.[173,660,1037,1639]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 8. Margarinotus thomomysi, median lobe of aedeagus. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Apical view of gonopore." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892950/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[202,228,608,629]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[709,741,658,677]" captionTargetBox="[691,1171,196,622]" captionTargetId="figure-472@9.[685,1172,163,634]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 10. Margarinotus sexstriatus and Margarinotus merdarius, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. sexstriatus, dorsal view. B. M. sexstriatus, lateral view. C. M. merdarius, apical view of gonopore. D. M. merdarius, dorsal view. E. M. merdarius, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892952" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892952/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">10</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingRegion box="[273,371,608,629]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">California</collectingRegion>
, they are the most common all-black 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gyllenhal" authorityYear="1808" box="[241,326,634,655]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Histerini">Histerini</taxonomicName>
, and the most common 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gyllenhal" authorityYear="1808" box="[555,637,634,655]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Histerini">Histerini</taxonomicName>
in general (though that is not to say that they are common â€“ they are rarely encountered). Of the five species of true 
<taxonomicName box="[293,352,712,733]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Hister" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[293,352,712,733]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Hister</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to occur in 
<collectingRegion box="[536,634,712,733]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">California</collectingRegion>
, none have a complete outer subhumeral stria, and only 
<taxonomicName authority="Horn" authorityName="Horn" authorityYear="1870" box="[199,396,765,786]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Hister" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="militaris">
<emphasis box="[199,342,765,786]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Hister militaris</emphasis>
Horn
</taxonomicName>
is fairly widespread, with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[151,341,791,812]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Hister" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abbreviatus">
<emphasis box="[151,341,791,812]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Hister abbreviatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
F. extending barely into the northern part of the state, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lewis" authorityName="Lewis" authorityYear="1888" box="[447,638,817,838]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Hister" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comes">
<emphasis box="[447,572,817,838]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Hister comes</emphasis>
Lewis
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Erichson" authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1834" box="[195,448,843,864]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Hister" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coenosus">
<emphasis box="[195,353,843,864]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Hister coenosus</emphasis>
Erichson
</taxonomicName>
extending into the more monsoonal-influenced extreme southeastern part of the state. Two species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lewis" authorityName="Lewis" authorityYear="1906" box="[465,638,896,917]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Spilodiscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[465,573,896,917]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Spilodiscus</emphasis>
Lewis
</taxonomicName>
occurring in 
<collectingRegion box="[282,381,922,943]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">California</collectingRegion>
exhibit red elytral maculations. The adventive 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kugelann)" baseAuthorityName="Kugelann" baseAuthorityYear="1792" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">
<emphasis box="[394,637,948,969]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Margarinotus obscurus</emphasis>
(Kugelann)
</taxonomicName>
has not yet been recorded in 
<collectingRegion box="[536,634,974,995]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">California</collectingRegion>
, but is known from 
<collectingRegion box="[346,462,1000,1021]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Washington</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[515,591,1000,1021]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Oregon</collectingRegion>
, and may occur in northern 
<collectingRegion box="[372,471,1027,1048]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">California</collectingRegion>
. This species has an abbreviated outer subhumeral elytral stria, and can only be assigned to the genus on the basis of genitalic and protibial characters.
</paragraph>
